			<title>Voter Fraud</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78484-Voter-Fraud&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 18 Feb 2016 14:26:27 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[As I'm sure many of you have watched John Oliver this week, it has left me with a substantial question that he brought up, but didn't answer.  Near the end of the video he talks about Ghost voting, where the elected official will cast a vote for a separate elected official.  They claim it's...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>As I'm sure many of you have watched John Oliver this week, it has left me with a substantial question that he brought up, but didn't answer.  Near the end of the video he talks about Ghost voting, where the elected official will cast a vote for a separate elected official.  They claim it's standard practice, and often the absentee has asked for it, but this is often not the case.  It's become such habit that they routinely just cast the votes.<br />
<br />
One of the clips even showed a representative being beaten to his own voting button.  In other words he was there, and someone else still cast his vote.  And Oliver insinuates that this can cross party lines and sometimes they may not even be aware of it.  If your back is turned someone my ghost vote your button, and after you turn around and cast your vote, have no idea it doesn't count.<br />
<br />
So the question is, how is this not blatantly illegal?  They are caught on camera all the time doing this.  I have never heard of this before John Oliver, but this is outright insanity to me.<br />
<br />
I get that they cast alot of votes, and maybe they can't be there for all of them, but that's the job.  It is their responsibility to be there or miss the vote.  Allowing this behavior, even if votes are always cast on the absentee's wish, is still voter fraud.<br />
<br />
Does anyone have more information about this?<br />
<br />

